nly |\n| **F-GROUP** (blank lines between logic groups) | Already followed | Code is well-paragraphed | — |\n| **F-OUT** (declare output vars first) | Inconsistent | Not a conscious convention | Manual review only |\n| **F-VISUAL** (blocks reflect business logic) | Mostly followed | Good use of `?` and early returns | — |\n| **F-PURE-MUT** (don't mix pure + mutation) | Mostly followed | No obvious violations | — |\n| **F-COMBINATOR** (no side effects in combinators) | Mostly followed | `for_each` rarely used | **Automatable** via `clippy.toml` `disallowed-methods` |\n\n### What's Worth Adopting\n\n**High value, easy to automate:**\n\n1. **`clippy.toml` with `disallowed-methods`** — ban `for_each`/`try_for_each` per F-COMBINATOR. Zero cost, prevents a real readability issue.\n\n2. **`clippy::self_named_module_files`** — this is the P-MOD lint. However, reme already consistently uses file-based modules. Adopting `mod.rs` style would mean touching every directory module. **Not worth migrating**, but the rule is worth noting for new directory modules.\n\n**Medium value, needs nightly rustfmt:**\n\n3. **`imports_granularity = \"Item\"`** (M-SINGLE-USE) — flattens grouped imports. Genuinely reduces merge conflicts. But it's **nightly-only** in rustfmt, so not viable for stable CI today.\n\n4. **`group_imports = \"StdExternalCrate\"`** (related to M-PRIV-PUB-USE) — also nightly-only.\n\n**Low value / manual discipline only:**\n\n5. M-CALLER-CALLEE, M-PUB-PRIV ordering, F-OUT — these are good code review heuristics but have no automated enforcement. Documenting them in `CLAUDE.md` or a `CONTRIBUTING.md` is the only option.\n\n6. M-PRIV-USE (minimizing imports) — opinionated and would fight against the existing codebase style. Not worth adopting.\n\n### Recommended Actions\n\n**Concrete changes I'd suggest:**\n\n1. **Create `clippy.toml`** with the `disallowed-methods` config — this is the only automatable rule that adds real value:\n\n```toml\ndisallowed-methods = [\n    { path = \"std::iter::Iterator::for_each\", reason = \"Use `for` loops for side-effects (F-COMBINATOR)\" },\n    { path = \"std::iter::Iterator::try_for_each\", reason = \"Use `for` loops for side-effects (F-COMBINATOR)\" },\n]\n```\n\n2. **Add a note to `CLAUDE.md`** under coding conventions referencing the ordering heuristics (M-TYPE-ASSOC, M-ASSOC-TRAIT, M-PUB-PRIV, M-CALLER-CALLEE) as review guidelines — not hard rules, but principles agents and contributors should follow.\n\n3. **Don't adopt P-MOD** — the codebase is consistent with file-based modules and migrating would be churn for no gain. The style guide's reasoning (atomic units) is valid but the ship has sailed.\n\n4. **Don't adopt M-SINGLE-USE** until `imports_granularity` hits stable rustfmt — fighting the formatter is worse than grouped imports.\n\n### What's NOT applicable\n\n- **P-PRELUDE-MOD** — no preludes exist, not relevant\n- **P-PATH** — already clean\n- **M-PRIV-USE** (minimal imports) — too opinionated, would require rewriting most files, marginal benefit in a project without heavy contributor churn\n- **F-OUT** — good principle but not enforceable; the codebase is already well-structured\n\n### Bottom Line\n\nMost of epage's guide is already followed organically. The codebase has good structure. The one concrete automation win is the `clippy.toml` for `disallowed-methods`. The ordering heuristics are worth documenting as soft guidelines. The import style rules need nightly rustfmt and aren't worth the trade-off today.\n\nWant me to create the `clippy.toml` and/or update `CLAUDE.md` with the relevant guidelines?",
